The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Tuesday, March 23, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		The decomposed body of a 23-year-old businessman of Dum Dum, Manik Chakraborty, was recovered from Arjunpur canal, on the northern fringes of the city, three days after he went missing. Police suspect that one of Chakrabortys business rivals murdered and dumped his body in the canal. Police are trying to find out whether Chakraborty, a building materials supplier, had become involved in a professional rivalry. No one has been arrested yet.																																																		The city civic authorities have undertaken construction of a bathing ghat close to Fort William. According to mayor Subrata Mukherjee, the CMC had taken up a scheme in 2003 to construct seven bathing ghats on the Hooghly at an expenditure of Rs 2 crore. Of the seven ghats, the one coming up beside Fort William at a cost Rs 30 lakh would be called the mayors ghat.																																																		Fire broke out on Monday evening at Tiljala Road in Park Circus in a chemical store and spread to an adjacent warehouse stocking leather scrap. Police said it took six fire-tenders nearly half-an-hour to douse the flames. No casualty was reported.																																																		A 30-year-old housewife, Amina Bibi, was hacked to death on Sunday night at Baruipur, on the southern fringes of the city, by a neighbour. Amina had reportedly repelled the neighbours advances. Police said Aminas husband Samsuddin Sheikh, who tried to save her, also suffered injuries and has been admitted to Baruipur Hospital. The assailant is absconding.																																																		A Group D employee of Medical College and Hospital, B. Mohan, was suspended on Saturday by the hospital authorities for allegedly accepting bribes at the outpatients department. He was handed over to the police. According to police, Mohan was produced in court on Monday and granted bail. 																																																		Auto-rickshaw driver Dilip Ghosh, 35, was shot on Sunday night at Keutia, in the Jagaddal police station area, on the northern fringes, by his friend, Swarnakamal Dutta. Police said the two residents of Nimta had travelled down to Keutia on Sunday night. In the course of a drinking bout, Dutta shot Ghosh with an improvised pipegun. Dutta was arrested. Ghosh is recuperating at Jawaharlal Nehru Hospital in Kalyani.																																																		Traffic was disrupted on Monday morning for more than two hours when Trinamul Congress workers blocked Diamond Harbour Road near Sarishahat following an accident in which two teenagers, Sushanto Mandal, 14, and Surojit Das, 15, were hit by a trailer. They are in a local nursing home.																																																		A 58-year-old railway employee, N. Singh, was injured on Monday morning at Kaiser Street in the Narkeldanga police station area when an awning of the railway quarters came crashing down on him. Singh was treated at a local clinic and later discharged.																																																		Three houses were burgled of cash and jewellery worth several lakhs on Sunday night at Gaighata, on the northern fringes of the city, by a gang of seven armed dacoits. According to police, when the miscreants robbed the residents of the three houses at gunpoint and entered the fourth house, the occupants raised an alarm. The robbers fled.																																																		A 50-year-old resident of Bagmari Road attempted suicide at the Shyambazar Metro station on Monday evening. He was spotted lying unconscious on the wooden plank beside the third rail at 6.55 pm. Power was shut off between Shyambazar and Belgachhia. The next Down train was stopped at Belgachhia. He was taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital.To Bhoruka Public Welfare Trust for receiving the ISO 9001: 2000 certificate
